[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Cocoa consists of the Foundation Kit, Application Kit, and Core Data frameworks, as included by the `Cocoa.h` header file, and the libraries and frameworks included by those, such as the C standard library and the Objective-C runtime.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Cocoa applications are typically developed using the development tools provided by Apple, specifically Xcode (formerly Project Builder) and Interface Builder (now part of Xcode), using the programming languages Objective-C or Swift.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] However, the Cocoa programming environment can be accessed using other tools.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] It is also possible to write Objective-C Cocoa programs in a simple text editor and build it manually with GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) or Clang from the command line or from a makefile.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] For end users, Cocoa applications are those written using the Cocoa programming environment.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Such applications usually have a familiar look and feel, since the Cocoa programming environment provides a lot of common UI elements (such as buttons, scroll bars, etc.), and automates many aspects of an application to comply with Apple's human interface guidelines.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] For iOS, iPadOS, tvOS, and watchOS, APIs similar to Application Kit, named UIKit and WatchKit, are available; they include gesture recognition, animation, and a different set of graphical control elements that are designed to accommodate the specific platforms they target.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Foundation Kit and Core Data are also available in those operating systems.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] It is used in applications for Apple devices such as the iPhone, the iPod Touch, the iPad, the Apple TV, and the Apple Watch.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Cocoa continues the lineage of several software frameworks (mainly the *App Kit* and *Foundation Kit*) from the NeXTSTEP and OpenStep programming environments developed by NeXT in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Apple acquired NeXT in December 1996, and subsequently went to work on the Rhapsody operating system that was to be the direct successor of OPENSTEP.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] It was to have had an emulation base for classic Mac OS applications, named *Blue Box*.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] The OpenStep base of libraries and binary support was termed *Yellow Box*.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Rhapsody evolved into Mac OS X, and the Yellow Box became Cocoa.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Thus, Cocoa classes begin with the letters *NS*, such as NSString or NSArray.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] These stand for the original proprietary term for the OpenStep framework, NeXTSTEP.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Much of the work that went into developing OpenStep was applied to developing Mac OS X, Cocoa being the most visible part.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] For example, NeXTSTEP and OpenStep used Display PostScript for on-screen display of text and graphics, while Cocoa depends on Apple's Quartz (which uses the Portable Document Format (PDF) imaging model, but not its underlying technology).
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Cocoa also has a level of World Wide Web support, including the NSURL and WebKit HTML classes, and others, while OpenStep had only rudimentary support for managed network connections via NSFileHandle classes and Berkeley sockets.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] The API toolbox was originally called “Yellow Box” and was renamed to Cocoa - a name that had been already trademarked by Apple.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Apple's *Cocoa* trademark had originated as the name of a multimedia project design application for children.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] The name was intended to evoke "Java for kids", as it ran embedded in web pages.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] The original "Cocoa" program was discontinued following the return of Steve Jobs to Apple.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] At the time, Java was a big focus area for the company, so “Cocoa” was used as the new name for “Yellow Box” because, in addition to the native Objective-C usage, it could also be accessed from Java via a bridging layer.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Even though Apple discontinued support for the Cocoa Java bridge, the name continued and was even used for the Cocoa Touch API.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] One feature of the Cocoa environment is its facility for managing dynamically allocated memory.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Foundation Kit's NSObject class, from which most classes, both vendor and user, are derived, implements a reference counting scheme for memory management.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Objects that derive from the NSObject root class respond to a `retain` and a `release` message, and keep a retain count.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] A method titled `retainCount` exists, but contrary to its name, will usually not return the exact retain count of an object.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] It is mainly used for system-level purposes.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Invoking it manually is not recommended by Apple.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] A newly allocated object created with `alloc` or `copy` has a retain count of one.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Sending that object a `retain` message increments the retain count, while sending it a `release` message decrements the retain count.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] When an object's retain count reaches zero, it is deallocated by a procedure similar to a C++ *destructor*.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] `dealloc` is not guaranteed to be invoked.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Starting with Objective-C 2.0, the Objective-C runtime implemented an optional garbage collector, which is now obsolete and deprecated in favor of Automatic Reference Counting (ARC).
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] In this model, the runtime turned Cocoa reference counting operations such as "retain" and "release" into no-ops.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] The garbage collector does not exist on the iOS implementation of Objective-C 2.0.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Garbage collection in Objective-C ran on a low-priority background thread, and can halt on Cocoa's user events, with the intention of keeping the user experience responsive.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] The legacy garbage collector is still available on Mac OS X version 10.13, but no Apple-provided applications use it.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] In 2011, the LLVM compiler introduced Automatic Reference Counting (ARC), which replaces the conventional garbage collector by performing static analysis of Objective-C source code and inserting retain and release messages as necessary.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Cocoa consists of three Objective-C object libraries called *frameworks*.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Frameworks are functionally similar to shared libraries, a compiled object that can be dynamically loaded into a program's address space at runtime, but frameworks add associated resources, header files, and documentation.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] The Cocoa frameworks are implemented as a type of bundle, containing the aforementioned items in standard locations.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] A key part of the Cocoa architecture is its comprehensive views model.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] This is organized along conventional lines for an application framework, but is based on the Portable Document Format (PDF) drawing model provided by Quartz.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] This allows creating custom drawing content using PostScript-like drawing commands, which also allows automatic printer support and so forth.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Since the Cocoa framework manages all the clipping, scrolling, scaling and other chores of drawing graphics, the programmer is freed from implementing basic infrastructure and can concentrate on the unique aspects of an application's content.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] The Smalltalk teams at Xerox PARC eventually settled on a design philosophy that led to easy development and high code reuse.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Cocoa's design is a fairly, but not absolutely strict application of MVC principles.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Under OpenStep, most of the classes provided were either high-level View classes (in AppKit) or one of a number of relatively low-level model classes like NSString.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Compared to similar MVC systems, OpenStep lacked a strong model layer.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] No stock class represented a "document," for instance.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] During the transition to Cocoa, the model layer was expanded greatly, introducing a number of pre-rolled classes to provide functionality common to desktop applications.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] In Mac OS X 10.3, Apple introduced the NSController family of classes, which provide predefined behavior for the controller layer.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] These classes are considered part of the Cocoa Bindings system, which also makes extensive use of protocols such as Key-Value Observing and Key-Value Binding.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] The term 'binding' refers to a relationship between two objects, often between a view and a controller.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Bindings allow the developer to focus more on declarative relationships rather than orchestrating fine-grained behavior.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] With the arrival of Mac OS X 10.4, Apple extended this foundation further by introducing the Core Data framework, which standardizes change tracking and persistence in the model layer.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] In effect, the framework greatly simplifies the process of making changes to application data, undoing changes when necessary, saving data to disk, and reading it back in.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] In providing framework support for all three MVC domains, Apple's goal is to reduce the amount of boilerplate or "glue" code that developers have to write, freeing up resources to spend time on application-specific features.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] In most object-oriented languages, calls to methods are represented physically by a pointer to the code in memory.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] This restricts the design of an application since specific *command handling* classes are needed, usually organized according to the chain-of-responsibility pattern.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] While Cocoa retains this approach for the most part, Objective-C's late binding opens up more flexibility.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Under Objective-C, methods are represented by a *selector*, a string describing the method to call.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] When a message is sent, the selector is sent into the Objective-C runtime, matched against a list of available methods, and the method's *implementation* is called.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Since the selector is text data, this lets it be saved to a file, transmitted over a network or between processes, or manipulated in other ways.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] The implementation of the method is looked up at runtime, not compile time.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] There is a small performance penalty for this, but late binding allows the same selector to reference different implementations.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] By a similar token, Cocoa provides a pervasive data manipulation method called *key-value coding* (KVC).
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] This allows a piece of data or property of an object to be looked up or changed at runtime by name.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] The property name acts as a key to the value.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] In traditional languages, this late binding is impossible.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] An object's type need not be known, yet any property of that object can be discovered using KVC.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Also, by extending this system using something Cocoa terms *key-value observing* (KVO), automatic support for undo-redo is provided.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Late static binding is a variant of binding somewhere between static and dynamic binding.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] The binding of names before the program is run is called static (*early*); bindings performed as the program runs are dynamic (*late* or *virtual*).
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] One of the most useful features of Cocoa is the powerful *base objects* the system supplies.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] As an example, consider the Foundation classes `NSString` and `NSAttributedString`, which provide Unicode strings, and the `NSText` system in AppKit, which allows the programmer to place string objects in the GUI.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] `NSText` and its related classes are used to display and edit strings.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Paragraph layout can be controlled automatically or by the user, using a built-in "ruler" object that can be attached to any text view.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Spell checking is automatic, using a system-wide set of language dictionaries.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Unlimited undo/redo support is built in.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Using only the built-in features, one can write a text editor application in as few as 10 lines of code.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] With new controller objects, this may fall towards zero.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] When extensions are needed, Cocoa's use of Objective-C makes this a straightforward task.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Objective-C includes the concept of "categories," which allows modifying existing class "in-place".
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Functionality can be accomplished in a category without any changes to the original classes in the framework, or even access to its source.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] In other common languages, this same task requires deriving a new subclass supporting the added features, and then replacing all instances of the original class with instances of the new subclass.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] The Cocoa frameworks are written in Objective-C.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Cocoa's need for runtime binding means many of Cocoa's key features are not available with Java.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] In 2005, Apple announced that the Java bridge was to be deprecated, meaning that features added to Cocoa in macOS versions later than 10.4 would not be added to the Cocoa-Java programming interface.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] At Apple Worldwide Developers Conference (WWDC) 2014, Apple introduced a new programming language named Swift, which is intended to replace Objective-C.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Originally, AppleScript Studio could be used to develop simpler Cocoa applications.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] However, as of Snow Leopard, it has been deprecated.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] It was replaced with AppleScriptObjC, which allows programming in AppleScript, while using Cocoa frameworks.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] The Cocoa programming environment can be accessed using other tools with the aid of bridge mechanisms such as PasCocoa, PyObjC, CamelBones, RubyCocoa, and a D/Objective-C Bridge.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] Third-party bindings available for other languages include AppleScript, Clozure CL, Monobjc and NObjective (C#), Cocoa# (CLI), Cocodao and D/Objective-C Bridge, LispWorks, Object Pascal, CamelBones (Perl), PyObjC (Python), FPC PasCocoa (Lazarus and Free Pascal), RubyCocoa (Ruby).
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] A Ruby language implementation named MacRuby, which removes the need for a bridge mechanism, was formerly developed by Apple, while Nu is a Lisp-like language that uses the Objective-C object model directly, and thus can use the Cocoa frameworks without needing a binding.
[src:beeware-toga/cocoa-api] There are also open source implementations of major parts of the Cocoa framework, such as GNUstep and Cocotron, which allow cross-platform Cocoa application development to target other operating systems, such as Microsoft Windows and Linux.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:beeware-toga/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] The mobile app development sector has experienced significant growth in Europe.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] A 2017 report from the Progressive Policy Institute estimated there were *1.89 million jobs* in the *app economy* across the European Union (EU) by January 2017, marking a 15% increase from the previous year.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] These jobs include roles such as mobile app developers and other positions supporting the app economy.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] To facilitate developing applications for mobile devices, and the consistency thereof, various approaches have been taken.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] Most companies that ship a product (e.g., Apple, iPod/iPhone/iPad) provide an official software development kit (SDK).
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] They may also opt to provide some form of software testing and/or quality assurance (QA).
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] In exchange for being provided the SDK or other tools, it may be necessary for a prospective developer to sign some form of non-disclosure agreement (NDA), which restricts the sharing of privileged information.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] As part of the development process, mobile user interface (UI) design is an essential step in the creation of mobile apps.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] Mobile UI designers consider constraints, contexts, screen space, input methods, and mobility as outlines for design.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] Constraints in mobile UI design, which include the limited attention span of the user and form factors such as a mobile device's screen size for a user's hand(s).
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] Mobile UI context includes signal cues from user activity, such as the location where or the time when the device is in use, that can be observed from user interactions within a mobile app.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] Such context clues can be used to provide automatic suggestions when scheduling an appointment or activity or to filter a list of various services for the user.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] The user is often the focus of interaction with their device, and the interface entails components of both hardware and software.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] User input allows for the users to manipulate a system, and the device's output allows the system to indicate the effects of the users' manipulation.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] Overall, mobile UI design's goal is mainly for an understandable, user-friendly interface.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] Functionality is supported by mobile enterprise application platforms or integrated development environments (IDEs).
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] Developers of mobile applications must also consider a large array of devices with different screen sizes, hardware specifications, and configurations because of intense competition in mobile hardware and changes within each of the platforms.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] Today, mobile apps are usually distributed via an official online outlet or marketplace (e.g., Apple: The App Store – Google: Google Play) and there is a formalized process by which developers submit their apps for approval and inclusion in those marketplaces.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] Historically, however, that was not always the case.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] Mobile UIs, or front-ends, rely on mobile back-ends to support access to enterprise systems.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] The mobile back-end facilitates data routing, security, authentication, authorization, working off-line, and service orchestration.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] This functionality is supported by a mix of middleware components, including mobile app servers, mobile backend as a service (MBaaS), and service-oriented architecture (SOA) infrastructure.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] The software development packages needed to develop, deploy, and manage mobile apps are made from many components and tools which allow a developer to write, test, and deploy applications for one or more target platforms.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] First party tools include official SDKs published by, or on behalf of, the company responsible for the design of a given hardware platform (e.g., Apple, Google, etc.), and any third-party software that is officially supported for the purpose of developing mobile apps for that hardware.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] With bring your own device (BYOD) becoming the norm within more enterprises, IT departments often need stop-gap, tactical solutions that layer atop existing apps, phones, and platform component.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] Many system-level components are needed to have a functioning platform for developing mobile apps.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] Criteria for selecting a development platform usually include the target mobile platforms, existing infrastructure, and development skills.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] When targeting more than one platform with cross-platform development, it is also important to consider the impact of the tool on the user experience.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] Performance is another important criterion, as research on mobile apps indicates a strong correlation between application performance and user satisfaction.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] Along with performance and other criteria, the availability of the technology and the project's requirements may drive the development between native and cross-platform environments.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] To aid the choice between native and cross-platform environments, some guidelines and benchmarks have been published.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] Typically, cross-platform environments are reusable across multiple platforms, leveraging a native container while using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript for the user interface.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] In contrast, native environments are targeted at one platform for each of those environments.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] For example, Android development occurs in the Eclipse IDE using Android Developer Tools (ADT) plugins, Apple iOS development occurs using the Xcode IDE with Objective-C and/or Swift, Windows and BlackBerry each have their own development environments.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] Mobile applications are first tested within the development environment using emulators and later subjected to field testing.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] Emulators provide an inexpensive way to test applications on mobile phones to which developers may not have physical access.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] The following are examples of tools used for testing applications across the most popular mobile operating systems.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] According to a 2020 Industry Report on Applications, 46% of mobile app users have stated that they have stopped using or uninstalled an app due to poor performance.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] Many patent applications are pending for new mobile phone apps.
[src:beeware-toga/mobile-app-development] Most of these are in the technological fields of business methods, database management, data transfer, and operator interface.
[src:beeware-toga/native-computing] Native software is built to be executed directly by processors that implement a compatible instruction set.
[src:beeware-toga/native-computing] A program that runs natively on one platform is runnable on another platform via an emulator if an emulator is available and, generally, with significant runtime speed degradation.
[src:beeware-toga/native-computing] For example, games for a Game Boy (typically distributed as a cartridge), generally run natively on a Game Boy which is relatively incompatible with other computer platforms.
[src:beeware-toga/native-computing] To run such a game on another processor, software that emulates the Game Boy hardware is required.
[src:beeware-toga/native-computing] Cross-platform software can run on multiple processors although possibly requiring it to be re-built for different target systems.
[src:beeware-toga/native-computing] A native application programming interface (API) provides direct access to an underlying technology.
[src:beeware-toga/native-computing] For example, the Windows Native API is an application programming interface specific for the Windows NT kernel, which provides access to some kernel functions which cannot be directly accessed through the more universal Windows API.
[src:beeware-toga/native-computing] A native virtual machine (VM) runs directly on hardware, without virtualization or virtualization at its lowest level.
[src:beeware-toga/native-computing] For example, with multiple levels of virtualization, the lowest level operating system – the one that actually maintains direct control of the hardware – is referred to as a "Native VM".
[src:beeware-toga/native-computing] Applied to data, native data formats or communication protocols are those supported by a certain computer hardware or software, with maximal consistency and minimal amount of additional components.
[src:beeware-toga/native-computing] For example, EGA and VGA video adapters *natively* support code page 437.
[src:beeware-toga/native-computing] This does not preclude supporting other code pages, but it requires either a font uploading or using graphic modes.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Guido van Rossum began working on Python in the late 1980s as a successor to the ABC programming language.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python 3.0, released in 2008, was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Beginning with Python 3.5, capabilities and keywords for typing were added to the language, allowing optional static typing.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] As of 2026, the Python Software Foundation supports Python 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13, and 3.14, following the project's annual release cycle and five-year support policy.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 is currently in the beta development phase, and the stable release is expected to launch in October 2026.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Earlier versions in the 3.x series have reached end-of-life and no longer receive security updates.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python has gained extensive use in the machine learning community.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] It is widely taught as an introductory programming language.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Since 2003, Python has consistently ranked among the top ten most popular programming languages in the TIOBE Programming Community Index, which ranks programming languages based on searches across 24 platforms.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python was conceived in the late 1980s by Guido van Rossum at Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica (CWI) in the Netherlands.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] It was designed as a successor to the ABC programming language, which was inspired by SETL, capable of exception handling and interfacing with the Amoeba operating system.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python implementation began in December 1989.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Van Rossum first released it in 1991 as Python 0.9.0.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] In January 2019, active Python core developers elected a five-member Steering Council to lead the project.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] The name *Python* derives from the British comedy series *Monty Python's Flying Circus*.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python 2.0 was released on 16 October 2000, featuring many new features such as list comprehensions, cycle-detecting garbage collection, reference counting, and Unicode support.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python 2.7's end-of-life was initially set for 2015, and then postponed to 2020 out of concern that a large body of existing code could not easily be forward-ported to Python 3.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] It no longer receives security patches or updates.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] While Python 2.7 and older versions are officially unsupported, a different unofficial Python implementation, PyPy, continues to support Python 2, i.e., "2.7.18+" (plus 3.11), with the plus signifying (at least some) "backported security updates".
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python 3.0 was released on 3 December 2008, and was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions, with some new semantics and changed syntax.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python 2.7.18, released in 2020, was the last release of Python 2.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Several releases in the Python 3.x series have added new syntax to the language, and made a few (considered very minor) backward-incompatible changes.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] As of May 2026, Python 3.14.6 is the latest stable release.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] All older 3.x versions had a security update down to Python 3.9.24 then again with 3.9.25, the final version in 3.9 series.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python 3.10 is, since November 2025, the oldest supported branch.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 has an alpha released, and Android has an official downloadable executable available for Python 3.14.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Releases receive two years of full support followed by three years of security support.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python is a multi-paradigm programming language.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Object-oriented programming and structured programming are fully supported, and many of their features support functional programming and aspect-oriented programming – including metaprogramming and metaobjects.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Many other paradigms are supported via extensions, including design by contract and logic programming.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python is often referred to as a *'glue language'* because it is purposely designed to be able to integrate components written in other languages.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python uses dynamic typing and a combination of reference counting and a cycle-detecting garbage collector for memory management.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] It uses dynamic name resolution (late binding), which binds method and variable names during program execution.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python's design offers some support for functional programming in the "Lisp tradition".
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] It has `filter`, `map`, and `reduce` functions; list comprehensions, dictionaries, sets, and generator expressions.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] The standard library has two modules (`itertools` and `functools`) that implement functional tools borrowed from Haskell and Standard ML.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] However, Python has received criticism for violating these principles and adding unnecessary language bloat.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Responses to these criticisms note that the Zen of Python is a guideline rather than a rule.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] The addition of some new features had been controversial: Guido van Rossum resigned as *Benevolent Dictator for Life* after conflict about adding the assignment expression operator in Python 3.8.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Nevertheless, rather than building all functionality into its core, Python was designed to be highly extensible through modules.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] This compact modularity has made it particularly popular as a means of adding programmable interfaces to existing applications.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Van Rossum's vision of a small core language with a large standard library and an easily extensible interpreter stemmed from his frustrations with ABC, which represented the opposite approach.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python claims to strive for a simpler, less-cluttered syntax and grammar, while giving developers a choice in their coding methodology.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python lacks `do .. while` loops, which Rossum considered harmful.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] In contrast to Perl's motto "there is more than one way to do it", Python advocates an approach where "there should be one – and preferably only one – obvious way to do it".
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] In practice, however, Python provides many ways to achieve a given goal.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] There are at least three ways to format a string literal, with no certainty as to which one a programmer should use.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python's developers typically prioritize readability over performance.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] For example, they reject patches to non-critical parts of the CPython reference implementation that would offer increases in speed that do not justify the cost of clarity and readability.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Execution speed can be improved by moving speed-critical functions to extension modules written in languages such as C, or by using a just-in-time compiler like PyPy.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Also, it is possible to transpile to other languages.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] However, this approach either fails to achieve the expected speed-up, since Python is a very dynamic language, or only a restricted subset of Python is compiled (with potential minor semantic changes).
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be a fun language to use.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] This goal is reflected in the name – a tribute to the British comedy group Monty Python – and in playful approaches to some tutorials and reference materials.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] For instance, some code examples use the terms "spam" and "eggs" (in reference to a Monty Python sketch), rather than the typical terms "foo" and "bar".
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] A common neologism in the Python community is *pythonic*, which has a broad range of meanings related to program style: Pythonic code may use Python idioms well; be natural or show fluency in the language; or conform with Python's minimalist philosophy and emphasis on readability.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] There are 3 kinds of PEPs, with those are being *standards track PEP*, *Informational PEP* and *Process PEP*s which has their own unique meanings.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] They were firstly introduced in 2000, inspired by other RfCs (requests for comments) and Desing Enhancement Proposals.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Most known PEPs are PEP – 1, PEP – 8, PEP – 20, PEP – 257 and others.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be an easily readable language.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Its formatting is visually uncluttered and often uses English keywords where other languages use punctuation.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Unlike many other languages, it does not use curly brackets to delimit blocks, and semicolons after statements are allowed but rarely used.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] It has fewer syntactic exceptions and special cases than C or Pascal.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python uses whitespace indentation, rather than curly brackets or keywords, to delimit blocks.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] An increase in indentation comes after certain statements; a decrease in indentation signifies the end of the current block.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Thus, the program's visual structure accurately represents its semantic structure.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] This feature is sometimes termed the off-side rule.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Some other languages use indentation this way; but in most, indentation has no semantic meaning.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] The recommended indent size is four spaces.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] The assignment statement (`=`) binds a name as a reference to a separate, dynamically allocated object.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Variables may subsequently be rebound at any time to any object.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] In Python, a variable name is a generic reference holder without a fixed data type; however, it always refers to *some* object with a type.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] This is called dynamic typing—in contrast to statically-typed languages, where each variable may contain only a value of a certain type.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python does not support tail call optimization or first-class continuations; according to Van Rossum, the language never will.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] However, better support for coroutine-like functionality is provided by extending Python's generators.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Before 2.5, generators were lazy iterators; data was passed unidirectionally out of the generator.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] From Python 2.5 on, it is possible to pass data back into a generator function; and from version 3.3, data can be passed through multiple stack levels.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] In Python, a distinction between expressions and statements is rigidly enforced, in contrast to languages such as Common Lisp, Scheme, or Ruby.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] A statement cannot be part of an expression; because of this restriction, expressions such as list and `dict` comprehensions (and lambda expressions) cannot contain statements.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] As a particular case, an assignment statement such as `a = 1` cannot be part of the conditional expression of a conditional statement.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python uses duck typing, and it has typed objects but untyped variable names.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Type constraints are not checked at definition time; rather, operations on an object may fail at usage time, indicating that the object is not of an appropriate type.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Despite being dynamically typed, Python is strongly typed, forbidding operations that are poorly defined (e.g., adding a number and a string) rather than quietly attempting to interpret them.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python allows programmers to define their own types using classes, most often for object-oriented programming.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] New instances of classes are constructed by calling the class, for example, `SpamClass()` or `EggsClass()`); the classes are instances of the metaclass `type` (which is an instance of itself), thereby allowing metaprogramming and reflection.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Before version 3.0, Python had two kinds of classes, both using the same syntax: *old-style* and *new-style*.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Current Python versions support the semantics of only the new style.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python supports optional type annotations.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] These annotations are not enforced by the language, but may be used by external tools such as **mypy** to catch errors.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python includes a module `typing` including several type names for type annotations.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Also, mypy supports a Python compiler called mypyc, which leverages type annotations for optimization.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python includes conventional symbols for arithmetic operators (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`), the floor-division operator `//`, and the modulo operator `%`.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] (With the modulo operator, a remainder can be negative, e.g., `4 % -3 == -2`.) Python also offers the `**` symbol for exponentiation, e.g.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] These operators work as in traditional mathematics; with the same precedence rules, the infix operators `+` and `-` can also be unary, to represent positive and negative numbers respectively.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Division between integers produces floating-point results.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] In Python terms, the `/` operator represents *true division* (or simply *division*), while the `//` operator represents *floor division.* Before version 3.0, the `/` operator represents *classic division*.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Rounding towards negative infinity, though a different method than in most languages, adds consistency to Python.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] For instance, this rounding implies that the equation `(a + b)//b == a//b + 1` is always true.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Also, the rounding implies that the equation `b*(a//b) + a%b == a` is valid for both positive and negative values of `a`.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] As expected, the result of `a%b` lies in the half-open interval [0, *b*), where `b` is a positive integer; however, maintaining the validity of the equation requires that the result must lie in the interval (*b*, 0] when `b` is negative.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python provides a `round` function for rounding a float to the nearest integer.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] For tie-breaking, Python 3 uses the *round to even* method: `round(1.5)` and `round(2.5)` both produce `2`.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python allows Boolean expressions that contain multiple equality relations to be consistent with general usage in mathematics.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] For example, the expression `a < b < c` tests whether `a` is less than `b` and `b` is less than `c`.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] C-derived languages interpret this expression differently: in C, the expression would first evaluate `a < b`, resulting in 0 or 1, and that result would then be compared with `c`.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python uses arbitrary-precision arithmetic for all integer operations.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] The `Decimal` type/class in the `decimal` module provides decimal floating-point numbers to a pre-defined arbitrary precision with several rounding modes.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] The `Fraction` class in the `fractions` module provides arbitrary precision for rational numbers.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Due to Python's extensive mathematics library and the third-party library NumPy, the language is frequently used for scientific scripting in tasks such as numerical data processing and manipulation.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Functions are created in Python by using the `def` keyword.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] A function is defined similarly to how it is called, by first providing the function name and then the required parameters.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] To assign a default value to a function parameter in case no actual value is provided at run time, variable-definition syntax can be used inside the function header.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python's large standard library is commonly cited as one of its greatest strengths.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] For Internet-facing applications, many standard formats and protocols such as MIME and HTTP are supported.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] The language includes modules for creating graphical user interfaces, connecting to relational databases, generating pseudorandom numbers, arithmetic with arbitrary-precision decimals, manipulating regular expressions, and unit testing.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Some parts of the standard library are covered by specifications—for example, the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI) implementation `wsgiref` follows PEP 333—but most parts are specified by their code, internal documentation, and test suites.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] However, because most of the standard library is cross-platform Python code, only a few modules must be altered or rewritten for variant implementations.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] As of 13 March 2025, the Python Package Index (PyPI), the official repository for third-party Python software, contains over 614,339 packages.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Most Python implementations (including CPython) include a read–eval–print loop (REPL); this permits the environment to function as a command line interpreter, with which users enter statements sequentially and receive results immediately.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Also, CPython is bundled with an integrated development environment (IDE) called IDLE, which is oriented toward beginners.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Other shells, including IDLE and IPython, add additional capabilities such as improved auto-completion, session-state retention, and syntax highlighting.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] CPython is the reference implementation of Python.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] This implementation is written in C, meeting the C11 standard since version 3.11.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Older versions use the C89 standard with several select C99 features, but third-party extensions are not limited to older C versions—e.g., they can be implemented using C11 or C++.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] CPython compiles Python programs into an intermediate bytecode, which is then executed by a virtual machine.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] CPython is distributed with a large standard library written in a combination of C and native Python.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] CPython is available for many platforms, including Windows and most modern Unix-like systems, including macOS (and Apple M1 Macs, since Python 3.9.1, using an experimental installer).
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Starting with Python 3.9, the Python installer intentionally fails to install on Windows 7 and 8; Windows XP was supported until Python 3.5.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Old Python versions unofficially support VMS (mostly supporting) and OpenVMS x86-64 has Python 3.10 support.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Platform portability was one of Python's earliest priorities.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] During development of Python 1 and 2, even OS/2 and Solaris were supported; since that time, support has been dropped for many platforms.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] All current Python versions (since 3.7) support only operating systems that feature multithreading, by now supporting not nearly as many operating systems (dropping many outdated) than in the past.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] All alternative implementations have at least slightly different semantics.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] For example, an alternative may include unordered dictionaries, in contrast to other current Python versions.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] As another example in the larger Python ecosystem, PyPy does not support the full C Python API.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Creating an executable with Python often is done by bundling an entire Python interpreter into the executable, which causes binary sizes to be massive for small programs, yet there exist implementations that are capable of truly compiling Python.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Stackless Python is a significant fork of CPython that implements microthreads.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] This implementation uses the call stack differently, thus allowing massively concurrent programs.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] A performance comparison among various Python implementations, using a non-numerical (combinatorial) workload, was presented at EuroSciPy '13.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] In addition, Python's performance relative to other programming languages is benchmarked by The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] There are several approaches to optimizing Python performance, despite the inherent slowness of an interpreted language.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python's development is conducted mostly through the *Python Enhancement Proposal* (PEP) process; this process is the primary mechanism for proposing major new features, collecting community input on issues, and documenting Python design decisions.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python coding style is covered in PEP 8.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Outstanding PEPs are reviewed and commented on by the Python community and the steering council.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Enhancement of the language corresponds with development of the CPython reference implementation.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] The mailing list python-dev is the primary forum for the language's development.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Specific issues were originally discussed in the Roundup bug tracker hosted by the foundation.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] In 2022, all issues and discussions were migrated to GitHub.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Development originally took place on a self-hosted source-code repository running Mercurial, until Python moved to GitHub in January 2017.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Many alpha, beta, and release-candidates are also released as previews and for testing before final releases.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Although there is a rough schedule for releases, they are often delayed if the code is not ready yet.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python's development team monitors the state of the code by running a large unit test suite during development.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] The major academic conference on Python is PyCon.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Also, there are special Python mentoring programs, such as PyLadies.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python's name is inspired by the British comedy group Monty Python, whom Python creator Guido van Rossum enjoyed while developing the language.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Monty Python references appear frequently in Python code and culture; for example, the metasyntactic variables often used in Python literature are *spam* and *eggs*, rather than the traditional *foo* and *bar*.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Also, the official Python documentation contains various references to Monty Python routines.
[src:beeware-toga/python-programming-language] Python users are sometimes referred to as "Pythonistas".
[src:beeware-toga/widget-toolkit] A **widget toolkit**, **widget library**, **GUI toolkit**, **GUI framework**, **UI framework**, or **UX library** is a library or a collection of libraries containing a set of graphical control elements (called *widgets*) used to construct the graphical user interface (GUI) of programs.
[src:beeware-toga/widget-toolkit] Most widget toolkits additionally include their own rendering engine.
[src:beeware-toga/widget-toolkit] This engine can be specific to a certain operating system or windowing system or contain back-ends to interface with multiple ones and also with rendering APIs such as OpenGL, OpenVG, or EGL.
[src:beeware-toga/widget-toolkit] The look and feel of the graphical control elements can be hard-coded or decoupled, allowing the graphical control elements to be themed/skinned.
[src:beeware-toga/widget-toolkit] Some toolkits may be used from other languages by employing language bindings.
[src:beeware-toga/widget-toolkit] Graphical user interface builders such as e.g.
[src:beeware-toga/widget-toolkit] Glade Interface Designer facilitate the authoring of GUIs in a WYSIWYG manner employing a user interface markup language such as in this case GtkBuilder.
[src:beeware-toga/widget-toolkit] The GUI of a program is commonly constructed in a cascading manner, with graphical control elements being added directly to on top of one another.
[src:beeware-toga/widget-toolkit] Most widget toolkits use event-driven programming as a model for interaction.
[src:beeware-toga/widget-toolkit] The toolkit handles user events, for example when the user clicks on a button.
[src:beeware-toga/widget-toolkit] When an event is detected, it is passed on to the application where it is dealt with.
[src:beeware-toga/widget-toolkit] The design of those toolkits has been criticized for promoting an oversimplified model of event-action, leading programmers to create error-prone, difficult to extend and excessively complex application code.
[src:beeware-toga/widget-toolkit] Finite-state machines and hierarchical state machines have been proposed as high-level models to represent the interactive state changes for reactive programs.
[src:beeware-toga/widget-toolkit] A window is considered to be a graphical control element.
[src:beeware-toga/widget-toolkit] In some windowing systems, windows are added directly to the scene graph (canvas) by the window manager, and can be stacked and layered on top of each other through various means.
[src:beeware-toga/widget-toolkit] Each window is associated with a particular application which controls the widgets added to its canvas, which can be watched and modified by their associated applications.
